http://rdfs.org/sioc/ns#content.value: A popular Japanese name, Emi means “reflect” and “beauty,” apt for the town’s turbulent history and present floriculture. The region suffered a cholera outbreak in the late 1800s, and was bombed and invaded by U.S. forces during the Second World War. Today, flower farms blanket the hills outside the village. In nearby Kamogawa, the Futomi Flower Center contains a garden and greenhouse with over two thousand plant species collected from around the world, from orchids to cacti. This living hub faces the Pacific Ocean just a few miles from the Tata Communications cable station in Emi, which joins Tokyo to the U.S. and the rest of Tata’s global network.

At the turn of the twenty-first century, three cables came ashore on the rural coast of western Oregon. While systems of the coaxial period usually terminated close to shore, these lines wind inland for over seventy miles, through the fir-populated mountains of the Tillamook State Forest to a Portland suburb nestled in the heart of “Silicon Forest.” The area was first granted this nickname in 1981, only a few years after Intel established a research campus there. Yet the seeds of Silicon Forest were planted much earlier. In the 1930s, the U.S. Forest Service Radio Lab was created in Portland, and developed wireless technologies to track fires as they spread through the forest, including the one that now borders the cable route. Engineers at the Radio Lab eventually developed two of Portland’s most well-known technology companies, setting the stage for today’s high-tech boom. Hillsboro, Oregon is now the home to many computer researchers, chip manufacturers, and cable stations, as well as a budding hub of data center activity. Companies are drawn to Silicon Forest because of its “welcoming” environment: not only do companies get massive tax breaks they in Hillsboro’s E-Commerce zone, but they have immediate access to cheap hydroelectric power from the nearby Columbia River.

The Piti cable station, built just down the road from Naval Base Guam, is a fiber-optic superstation. Financed during the cable boom and was built in 2002 to land the Tyco Transpacific Network, the building is enormous, though when you enter, the reception desk remains empty, occupied only by a small security camera. You move through a large, hollow room containing rows of empty cubicles, into expansive halls of equipment, and down a cavernous hallway. On one side of the hallway is a giant battery plant in which everything is red; this is the red plant. Round plate batteries are stacked in many rows. On the other side of the hallway is a mirror version of the same plant, but blue; this is the blue plant. The station stands in contrast to the clustered, layered, and remade spaces of the Cold War buildings, Tumon and Tanguisson, further north on the island. There are no photos on the wall, or anything to mark that you are on Guam. The station has been meticulously designed, completely redundant, and with more than enough power and space to land several other systems. The station, like many others, has been overbuilt in anticipation of future growth; afterward, the market crashed and no networks landed here until 2009. There is plenty of extra room to offer to other cable networks, data or call centers, and services for digital content generation.

Long before Toyohashi was linked to underwater cable systems, it belonged to a key pedestrian highway network. From the seventeenth to mid-nineteenth century, the town was one of fifty “post stations” or rest stops along the Tōkaidō, widely considered the most important of five government-sponsored roads that joined Tokyo (then known as Edo) to outlying territories. While contemporary signals pass through at the speed of light, travelers on the Tōkaidō paused in Toyohashi to buy supplies, visit teahouses, and find lodging on their journeys between Edo and Kyoto. The stations fell out of use when railroads expanded in the late 1800s, but the route remains a major transit corridor. Opened in 1964, the Tōkaidō Shinkasnsen is the most-traveled high-speed rail line in the world.

When it entered served in 2002, the TGN (Tyco Global Network) cable between Japan and the U.S. offered the highest capacity of any Pacific crossing. Messages travel along this route in a little as .022 seconds. TGN was acquired by the massive Indian company, Tata Communications, in 2005.

http://rdfs.org/sioc/ns#content.value: Landing at Ela Beach, it’s hard to believe you are in one of the most dangerous places in the Pacific. Blue-green waters lap up against the white sands, strewn with seaweed. Papuan children splash in the water and linger under palm trees. Traveling a bit farther up the coast, past a cargo terminal, to the Poreporena Villages, you find an entire shanty-town built on rotting stilts. The water here is less clear and the rocky beach is strewn with trash. Port Moresby, the capital city of Papua New Guinea, is riddled with poverty. Raskol gangs, known for armed robberies, roam the streets and clash with the police, who have an equally violent reputation. The murder rate in this city of 250,000 is three times that of London. Just across the Coral Sea from Australia, the city has been the entry way for Papua New Guinea’s cable communications since 1976 – an infrastructure that many had hoped would contribute to development and better lives for the country’s citizens.

http://rdfs.org/sioc/ns#content.value: Like many port cities in Asia, Nagasaki was “discovered” by imperial powers – in this case, the Portuguese – and developed for trade. In the nineteenth century, Nagasaki became a busy transit point, with a vibrant ship-building industry, an anchorage site for the Japanese navy, and a telegraph cable landing point. Three years after its first submarine telegraph cable was landed in 1871, the telegraph company established a headquarters here, in a large two-story office building abutting the harbor. Within a few years, Japan would build up its internal landlines, and the country would be connected to the rest of the world via Nagasaki. The importance of this station was clear to Japan and its enemies. Described as “clutching the aeortic artery of international communications in Japan,” Nagasaki, as a hub and military harbor, was also a target. The cable to Vladivostok was taken out of service during the Russo-Japanese War, but the city remained undamaged. During World War II, however, Nagasaki was hit with the atomic bomb, the second and last to ever be deployed, killing several hundred thousand people. After the Japanese surrender, the city would slowly rebuild. Old communications lines were taken out of service, and new coaxial cables laid in their place.

http://rdfs.org/sioc/ns#content.value: Although it started out as a small farm town, Shanghai grew into an important and busy port during the Qing Dynasty. In 1842, after the British defeated the Chinese in the first Opium War, Shanghai became a treaty port, occupied by British forces and open for international trade. Throughout the end of the 19th and beginning of the 20th centuries, the city grew rapidly. Tall municipal buildings and three-story stone houses with red roofs lined the wide and busy streets. The ports were congested with naval and trade ships from Britain, France, and Japan. The first telegraph cable arrived in 1871, connecting the city to Singapore and Hong Kong. As the cable was laid up the Yangtze River to Shanghai, men armed with rifles patrolled it to stop sailors from throwing anchor and severing the connection. By 1916, ten more cables - sponsored by a range of governments and militaries - had landed here, linking to Japan, Russia, Yap, the Philippines, and other Chinese ports.

http://rdfs.org/sioc/ns#content.value: Bondi Beach is perhaps better known as a world famous surfing locale than as a hotspot for cable landing. Since the early twentieth century, however, Bondi has been the landing point for numerous telegraph, telephone, and fiber-optic cable systems. Located right near the center of Sydney, Bondi offers proximity for cable layers that seek to move in close to downtown markets. The most difficult part for cable companies is getting from the coastal beaches where cables land to Sydney's central cable station. Given the lack of duct space under the streets, this makes it difficult to lay new systems directly into major cities.

Oxford Falls is a center of coordination, a place where seemingly opposed forces depend on one another: human and non-human, wired and wireless, and major telecommunications competitors. A relatively rural area north of Sydney, Oxford Falls was a satellite gateway well before it was a hub for wired infrastructure. In 1987, the government-owned Overseas Telecommunication Commission selected this valley for a satellite earth station in part because the surrounding forest, densely vegetated with native species, naturally protected aerial signals from radiointerference. Eight years later, the earth station’s major competitor, Optus, set up a second facility just down the road. As nature shielded human communication and as competitors paved the way for one another, wireless forms also set the stage for wired links. In the years that followed, major international cable networks terminated in Oxford Falls, interconnecting with rather than eliminating the older satellite arrays.

The Australia-Japan Cable (AJC) links the two countries via Guam. When it was completed in 2001, it became “Australia’s largest connection yet to the global information highways,” according to an industry newsletter. The cable reaches depths of over 9,000 meters and forms a “collapsed ring” structure with twin lines spanning each leg of the system. A private company owned by Japanese and Australian telecoms was set up to design, build, and operate the cable until its projected retirement in 2026.

http://rdfs.org/sioc/ns#content.value: Remains of stone-age cultures have been found in Fuzhou, dating back to 5000 B.C.E. Over the millennia, many civilizations have arisen and fallen on this land. In the 10th century, tall pagodas were erected to protect the city from “evil influences of atmospheric currents.” Such currents brought human trouble more than atmospheric calamity, as the site became desirable to foreign imperial powers. The waterways that run along the city make it ideal for trading and transportation, while the rich, wet earth cultivates rice fields, and the nearby island-protected harbors provide good anchor for military and trade ships. By the 19th century, Fuzhou had grown into a large walled city with a population of over half a million. Westerners ran major trade operations from the city following the British victory in the first Opium War, which opened the port – then called Foochow – to foreign trade. More recently, the area has been opened to foreign circulations in another way: Fuzhou has been declared a free trade zone, and a new fiber-optic cable lands there linking to Taiwan. As goods and signals flow in and out freely, the economy has become less stable. Fuzhou is now known for supplying America with a labor force, as young adults from its suburbs come to the United States to work long hours at low wages.

http://rdfs.org/sioc/ns#content.value: The Batam cable station looks out across rusty brown sand and a dark blue sea. Somewhere across that water is Singapore, where the other end of the cable has landed since 2006. The station shares the shore with many other industries – nearby you glimpse silhouettes of cranes and oil rigs. Not much farther along the coast there are ship-repair yards and a number of ferry ports. Fiber-optic signals run underneath, and support, the transfer of goods and people to and from Singapore on the water's surface. Part of a free trade zone, the whole area is a bit lassiez-faire. Batam does not exert a large amount of control over the information, commerce, or people that stream in and out. The city itself serves the appetites of the workers and businessmen who have come to build up these industries, offering restaurants, bars, and an infamous nightlife. Even the taxis and the driving speeds remain unregulated.

Landing at one of two designated sites on the northern and southern coasts of Changi, you make your way inland to a cluster of stations that form East Singapore’s primary cable hub. Today, the area is known for its major international airport complex, which includes a cactus garden, butterfly habitat, and what will soon be the world’s largest indoor waterfall. But this cutting-edge cable and aviation crossroads has a dark history. The British established a military base at Changi in the early 1900s when the peninsula was still mostly swampland and forests of tall “chengei” trees. During its occupation of Singapore in World War II, Japan used the compound to imprison thousands of captured Allied soldiers. (The prison was rebuilt in the 1990s and now has a death-row detention center.) Even the northern beaches where cables come ashore, a popular spot for picnics and watersports, were the setting for a brutal 1942 massacre of Chinese Singaporeans thought to be anti-Japanese.

In the 1920s, a submarine cable manufactured by the German company Norddeutsche Seekabelwerke and sponsored by the Dutch East Indies government was laid down the western coast of Sulawesi, connecting Dutch settlements on the island to Surabaya.

“The view of the harbor in clear weather is beautiful and animated,” notes an 1897 travel guide to Surabaya. Under Dutch rule since 1743, it was the main commercial port and largest Dutch naval base in the East Indies. “On the water and along the quays great bustle prevails. . . . Chinese and Javanese, Europeans and Arabs, citizens and soldiers mingle” in the crowded streets. The arrival of two Dutch submarine cables in 1913 and 1921 brought the city into further contact with other settlements in the region. But Surabaya’s growth and vibrancy was interrupted by conflict in the 1940s. The city was captured by the Japanese and bombed by Allied forces in the Second World War. And in the 1945 Battle of Surabaya, Indonesian soldiers fought British troops for national independence. This history of profound struggle resonates with the name Surabaya, which some say derives from a mythical battle between two powerful creatures, a “sura” (shark) and a “baya” (crocodile).

Like so many Indonesian cities, Makassar developed under the influence of European spice trades starting in the 16th century. The Dutch came in the 17th century and the cables began to arrive in the late 19th century, connecting this city with Bali in 1888, Balikpapan in 1905, and then with Java and Central Sulawesi in 1913. Arriving along the cable at the turn of the twentieth century, you witness the height of Dutch development: they had captured, rebuilt, and renamed the city’s central fort. The new “Fort Rotterdam” looked very much like its namesake, with manicured lawns and large stone buildings with pitched red roofs. The walled city that developed around the fort was a hub for the copra, rattan, pearls, trepang, and sandalwood trade, and enslaved local people for businessmen. Although Joseph Conrad called Makassar “the prettiest and perhaps, cleanest looking of all the towns in the islands,” such beauty reflected colonial interests.

“The little village of Donggala, capital of the ‘kingdom of Palos,’ as it is called in books, lies most picturesquely at the foot of the green chalk rocks along the narrow beach,” notes a guide to the Dutch East Indies from 1897. In the early 1900s, Donggala flourished as the principle harbor for the Bay of Palos (now known as the Bay of Palu) in Central Sulawesi. Coffee and coconuts grown in the surrounding hills were exported in large quantities, and various goods were traded by sea and land. A Dutch cable arrived in 1921 linking the town to area settlements. During the Second World War, however, Palu became the provincial capital and trade flows shifted south. As a result, Donggala is still the small and picturesque seaport it was at the turn of the century.

Menado derives from the word manadou or wanazou, meaning “on the far coast” or “in the distance.” The town is located on the far northwestern tip of the Indonesian island North Sulawesi. The Dutch East India Company built a fortress here in 1658 and from that time it was slowly and steadily colonized and Christianized by traders and missionaries. The thick stone walls of the city’s fort still exist, but outside it, the town has grown into a colonial village with hedgerows, streets, gardens, and cottages. In 1905, traveling via Menado’s first undersea cable, you traverse a busy port filled with large trading vessels and smaller, slimmer pinisiq, Indonesian sailboats. The beautiful bay actually makes a bad harbor: the reefs and steep slope in the sea floor make it difficult to anchor. Between the cable landing and the distant mountaintops, expansive coffee plantations have developed. Although it will never grow into a sizeable port city, this location will remain important to the Dutch in part due to its massive coffee exports.

Typhoons and loneliness were the greatest perils for the cablemen working on the Cocos Islands in the early and middle twentieth century. Like Midway Island, the Cocos were largely uninhabited before the establishment of a cable station in 1901. The station was built at the highest point on the island: two meters above the high water mark, but this didn't keep it from damage during cyclones in 1907, 1911, and 1933. These caused flooding, collapsed palm trees onto the cable station houses, and wreaked havoc for international communications. During quieter moments, cablemen played tennis, worked, and waited eagerly for the arrival of supply ships every three months to bring food, mail, and mild excitement. Today, tourists seek out the Cocos for their quietude and isolation, sparsely and silently scattering themselves across the white beaches and blue-green waters. Floating just above the ocean’s surface, these low-lying islands still hold tropical forests, surrounded by soft beaches. There are no hills or mountains on the Cocos, and pools of fresh water collect here and there in the soil when it rains. True to their name, the islands’ sole export is coconuts, which hang heavily from palm trees everywhere you look.

http://rdfs.org/sioc/ns#content.value: Weltevreden, Batavia is today’s Sawah Besar, a section of Jakarta, Indonesia. The area was built up and named by the Dutch East India Company in the 17th and 18th centuries. In the 19th Century it became a full-fledged Dutch colony and in 1859 a telegraph cable was laid here connecting to Hong Kong. Had you arrived at that time, you would have found an established colonial city with a busy port. The area closer to the water held warehouses and offices of many trading companies. Weltevreden was more stately, with shops and government offices. Writings from that period describe the cable station as “one of the favourite stations in the Extension Co.” – it had a rambling garden, tennis courts, stables, a reading room, and a broad entryway flanked by palm trees. Today the area still bears traces of the earlier colonial period. The central square, laid out by the Dutch in the 19th century, displays symmetrical paths and gardens lined with palm trees, which lead to a statue celebrating Indonesia’s independence. In the same neighborhood, a large cathedral sits nearby a temple that is home to both Buddhist and Hindu practitioners, built in Dutch Colonial style.

http://rdfs.org/sioc/ns#content.value: Electric Beach, on O‘ahu’s west shore, is named for the large power plant towering behind it and known for regular car burglaries. Three men casually fish off the edge of the point. Families barbeque. A manhole is covered in rusty red dirt. Moving under this manhole, through the cable, and out to the ocean, you briefly pass a small cave with hanging clothes, stockpiled chairs, and collected water. The same beach that makes possible the landing of communications cables – infrastructures that accelerate the movement of information across the oceans – is also a temporary dwelling for some of the least mobile Hawaiians. The Kahe Point station, constructed just north of Electric Beach, has managed to stay out of view, and therefore out of local politics.

You land in Spencer Beach Park, a gentle, sandy beach in a protected inlet on the northwestern tip of the island of Hawai‘i. The ocean is calm and clear. Snorkelers glide across the surface, peering at the colorful fish who dart through the waters below. Closer to shore, children splash around and wade up to the sand, where their families are picnicking. A bit farther inland, some campers sit at the opening of their tent and watch the ocean. Hawai‘i, “the big island” in the archipelago that makes up the state of Hawai‘i, is more sparsely populated than O’ahu, where the older the Hawaiian cables have landed. While recent cables encountered opposition from locals when they landed in O’ahu, at Spencer Beach there were celebrations upon arrival of a system from Tahiti, featuring traditional Hawaiian dance and song.

http://rdfs.org/sioc/ns#content.value: "It's either feast or famine," one cable station technician tells you. The history of the cable industry confirms this: it is littered with booms and busts. Cables are subject to risk and speculation. The most recent cable boom occurred in the late 1990s, alongside the dot com boom. Cable companies put massive amounts of fiber into the ocean. The privitization and deregulation of international telecommunications enabled new players to enter the network.

Fiber optic systems, which encode signals in light and send them down a thread of glass, have been in development since the early 1980s. Given the conservatism of the industry, the first international system was not put in place until 1986. The immense capacity of these systems have made possible the internet as we know it today.

The Southern Cross Cable Network was designed as an Internet-based cable that, at the time, would be the fastest and most straightforward route from Australia and New Zealand to the United States. Just as Southern Cross was being put in the water, the cable market collapsed – this was brought on by a combination of the excess capacity offered by the numerous cable systems laid in the late 1990s. The timing of Southern Cross was “perfect,” as its builders recollect, poised on the crest of the cable boom: if they'd started a little bit later, it likely wouldn't have happened.

http://rdfs.org/sioc/ns#content.value: The Telekom Malysia (TM) cable landing station at Mersing is situated on an otherwise undeveloped beach roughly six miles south of the town center. Large signage on a curved, blue glass awning and a flag bearing the TM logo ensure that the site is highly visible from the coastal highway that passes nearby. Since the late 1990s, it has housed cables linking southeastern Malaysia to the rest of Asia, the U.S., the Middle East, and Western Europe. On their journey east, these cables intersect the offshore Seribuat Archipelago, for which Mersing’s ferry terminal is the main point of departure. As Malays, tourists, and communication signals are carried out to sea, north-south trade routes link Mersing to the rest of the Malay Peninsula as a site of tin, rubber, and palm oil production.

Asia-America Gateway (AAG), opened in 2009, was the first high-bandwidth optical cable to provide a direct link between Southeast Asia and California (via the Philippines, Guam, and Hawaii). Positioned further south than other trans-Pacific routes, AAG avoids the seismically active areas near Taiwan where earthquakes are known to cause cable disruptions.

http://rdfs.org/sioc/ns#content.value: Before it was cleared for industrial development in the 1970s, Tuas was a small but active fishing village on the western tip of Singapore. Local fishermen would lay palm fronds on the water’s surface above a submerged net, attracting fish with the shade. The name “Tuas” derives from the Malay word for hauling up the net and the catch it contains. Although this technique is rarely practiced anymore, modern-day Tuas pulls together large-scale networks of various kinds. Global cable systems arrived starting in the late 1990s, connecting to the red and white SingTel station, adorned with a series of porthole-shaped windows and a tall, latticework communications tower. A power plant feeds Singapore’s grid with roughly a fifth of its total supply. Near-constant marine traffic flows through the naval base, shipyards, and container port, while waste is transferred to an offshore landfill. And roadways converge at a checkpoint and mile-long bridge that links Tuas to Johor, Malaysia, offering one of the only terrestrial paths off the island.

http://rdfs.org/sioc/ns#content.value: As a landing site for the 1983 ASEAN cable, Songkhla was the first station in Thailand to receive underwater telephone links. Cables surface on the idyllic Ban Kao Seng beach near the country’s largest natural lake, the same place where invading Japanese troops landed at the start of the Second World War. Years earlier, according to local folklore, a wealthy governor from the south of Thailand was sailing up the coast with a fortune in gold when his ship ran aground near Ban Kao Seng. Stranded, the governor ordered his fortune buried, committed suicide, and left instructions for his severed head to be placed on the rocky cliffs above the beach. The name Kao Seng derives from the treasure’s supposed value: 900,000 baht. Some believe it’s still buried there alongside several underwater cables entering the Gulf of Thailand.

The consortium-owned Southeast Asia Japan Cable (SJC) runs from Singapore to Japan, with branch connections to Thailand, Brunei, the Philippines, Hong Kong, and China. Intense demand along the communication route prompted capacity upgrades less than a year after it was built in 2013.
Following a link from Nagasaki to Tsingtau, the Japanese Military laid a cable between Tsingtau to Sasebo, where their Naval Base was located.

Sasebo became an essential node for military communications at the turn of the twentieth century. This Japanese port is about 100 miles south of the southern tip of Korea, across the ocean from Shanghai. The town had been a small fishing village until the Meiji Period, when it quickly became an important naval base because of its protected, nearly land-locked, deep harbor. In 1898, a major railway station was opened here, anticipating the other traffic to come. Cables came in from Port Arthur, and out across the East China Sea to Dairen and Tsingtau. The town grew up around the transiting traffic, becoming a busy port and a wireless station. Like many other hubs in the Pacific, its connectivity would become a liability in future years. The wireless station here is believed to have broadcasted the message to attack Pearl Harbor during World War II. Four years later, Sasebo suffered severe bombing by allied forces, and was on the list of potential targets for the dropping of the atom bomb.

http://rdfs.org/sioc/ns#content.value: When China began to struggle against imperialism in the late 1800s, Qingdao was an important node of resistance. The Boxers, an anti-imperialist, proto-nationalist Chinese movement, had a strong presence in area, and in 1897, the Chinese government began building up a military base here to protect against foreign invasion. Shortly thereafter, German troops seized and occupied this fort. After a year of fighting, China conceded the area to Germany, who re-named the city Tsingtau, a French transliteration of the original name. This small Chinese fishing village was transformed into a German administrative and economic center, with tall three-story stone buildings, wide streets, electricity, and a navy base. At the turn of the century, two telegraph cables were landed, one connecting to Tschifu and one to Shanghai. Today, two major cable systems continue to land at Qingdao, linking the city to Korea and across the sea to California.

http://rdfs.org/sioc/ns#content.value: For decades, Taiwan’s cables had been concentrated at its northern and southern tips. While the Tanshui and Toucheng stations are on the fringes of Taipei, the Chunghwa Telecom station is located in the rural southern township of Fangshan. Most traffic to Southeast Asia, whether from Taiwan, East Asia, or North America, passes through the Bashi Strait, the narrow passage separating Taiwan and the Philippines. Fangshan was the ideal gateway to this route until recently, when a spate of natural disasters severed numerous cable links. An earthquake in September 1999 broke Taiwan’s terrestrial backbone, one undersea cable, and caused cell sites and radio relays to collapse. The 2006 Hengchun earthquake caused submarine landslides that took out nine undersea links. Most recently,  Typhoon Morakot disrupted six international cables and 1700 wireless base stations, in addition to taking 500 lives. Fangshan, perched on the edge of the Bashi Strait, is no longer a popular interconnection point for undersea traffic.

EAC-C2C represents the merger of the EAC (East Asia Crossing) and C2C (City-to-City) cable networks, completed in 2007 by Pacnet. Together, they form Asia’s largest privately owned cable system with a total of seventeen landing sites across Japan, Korea, China, Taiwan, Hong Kong, the Philippines, and Singapore.

http://rdfs.org/sioc/ns#content.value: Kitaibaraki thrived as a center of coal mining in the nineteenth century, with rail lines connecting it to Tokyo a hundred miles away. In 2011, a 9.0-magnitude earthquake devastated the city. The closest cable station to the epicenter, Kitaibaraki was severed from both the U.S. and Asian networks, though Japan’s cable density allowed much of the traffic to be rerouted. The tsunami also wiped out an important cultural landmark: a red pagoda-like meditation retreat designed by Japanese philosopher and art historian Tenshin Okakura. While this structure was rebuilt in its original location on the rocky shores of the Pacific Ocean, cable operator KDDI announced the construction of a new tsunami-resistant station in Chikura that will stand ninety feet above sea level.

You can journey to the village of Maruyama along cables from the U.S., Australia, or various sites in Southeast Asia. But upon reaching the station, you may feel as if you’ve traveled even farther—and back in time. Across the road is Rosemary Park, a detailed replica of a sixteenth-century English town. Built in 1997 by British architects, the tourist attraction includes a working windmill, formal gardens, a duck pond, and a recreation of Shakespeare’s childhood home, complete with lifelike statues and time-specific furnishings. Shakespeare referenced rosemary in his plays, and Maruyama is known for producing this and other herbs. While the park looks to the past, the modern cable station is one of Japan’s most popular landing sites. Both enact a kind of virtual transit to far-off locales.

Shima is a major hub with connections to six active international cable networks, but it remains largely invisible to local residents. While cables are hidden, several festivals call attention to the surrounding ocean, known for its abundant marine life since at least the eighth century. Every June, a twenty-foot wooden spiny lobster is paraded through the city streets to encourage a bountiful harvest season. And in September, four men carry an oversized waraji (traditional straw sandal) into the ocean, setting it adrift. This ritual is designed to ward off Dandarabocchi, a mythological giant so large that his footsteps create lakes. Afterwards, spectators gather on the beach for dancing and a fireworks display.

http://rdfs.org/sioc/ns#content.value: Cables from Singapore, Malaysia, and the Philippines surfaced here in the early 1990s, followed by connections reaching as far as the U.S. and Western Europe. A link to the Asia-America Gateway in 2009 created an oversupply of bandwidth, which the Brunei government sold to international carriers in order to finance new cable landings. Located a few miles north of the capital, the station is at once remote and central, surrounded by trees but also a highway exchange and the campuses of both the University of Brunei and an international boarding school. Across the street, a fifteen-story glass office tower (and the second tallest building in the country) contains the headquarters of local telecom provider DataStream Technology Group. When cables arrived on nearby Tungku Beach in the 1990s, illegal sand mining had caused severe erosion. But the jagged shoreline has been restored and is now a popular place for watching sunsets.

http://rdfs.org/sioc/ns#content.value: As you approach Colombo, Ceylon (present-day Sri Lanka) in 1903, your travel guide tells you: “its appearance is extremely picturesque: a fine undulating country, well wooded to the water’s edge and fringed by cocoa-nut trees; lofty verdant ranges tower in the distance, covered with groves of talipat and other palms.” Centrally positioned in the Indian Ocean, Colombo was a key trade port long before the colonial era. In the early 1500s, the Portuguese established a fort and trading post to capitalize on the island’s abundant cinnamon crops. After a brief Dutch occupation, Colombo was ceded to the British and became the capital of British Ceylon. To facilitate faster communication to London, a submarine cable was brought to the island via the Middle East in 1913, connecting to a new Central Telegraph Office in a three-story wood building near the harbor. Messages could now travel between the two cities in as little as thirty minutes, a savings of nearly four hours compared to older land-based routes through India. Today, messages transit in only milliseconds from five cable systems that land in the Colombo area.

http://rdfs.org/sioc/ns#content.value: In George Town at the turn of the 19th century you witness the beginnings of a modern city. The streets are lined with warehouses and ghauts, wide steps leading from the street to the water. Banks, trading areas, and emporium stores are beginning to appear along Beach Street. Since its founding by the British East India Company in 1786, the town has grown into a bustling trading port and commercial center. George Town has been built on water: its commercial center stands on a swampy wetland that was leveled and filled in the early 1800s. Seeing that this was precarious, English settlers built their bungalows high up on top of Penang Hill, forbidding natives to do the same. The settlers’ wealthy Chinese business partners were allowed to build in the middle part of the hill. The cable – part of the emerging modern city – surfaces close to the water, but ultimately connected those who lived far above it.

http://rdfs.org/sioc/ns#content.value: The modern two-story cable station and data center, built to withstand severe weather, sits across the road from a rocky beach in the quiet suburb of Sopu, due west of central Nuku’alofa. Between 1978 and 2013, when a fiber-optic link to Fiji was completed, Tonga relied entirely on satellite connections. Internet access was slow, expensive, and used by less than a fifth of the population. But with a capacity six thousand times greater than satellite, the cable is set to lower costs and stimulate business investment, bringing more of the country online than ever before. Although it entered the underwater network only recently, Nuku’alofa has long been a regional hub. The deep natural harbor bounded by coral reefs is still Tonga’s main port and a gateway to the rest of the archipelago. Not far from the sleek landing station, the reefs are littered with the rusted hulls of old fishing vessels carried ashore by past storms.

This cable, which links Tonga to Fiji and the entire Southern Cross trans-Pacific network, was completed in August 2013 with major funding from the Asian Development Bank and World Bank. Run by the government-owned Tonga Cable Limited, it is part of a larger effort to connect smaller island nations in the Pacific.

In 1962, the balance of undersea cable power was shifting from British companies to the United States. The Keawa‘ula cable station had just been built on O‘ahu’s west shore to land the Commonwealth Pacific Cable. British transoceanic lines no longer stopped at Fanning Island, but rely on the United States. As such, its construction followed U.S. military specifications: it was located underground in a nuclear fallout shelter with walls that were feet thick. Arriving at this station today, you see an elegant set of steps up leading up to a front wall comprised of square glass blocks. One transmission engineer describes Keawa‘ula as a “palace.” Designed by a local Honolulu-based firm, the station's aboveground expansion was inspired by a visit from the CEO of Teleglobe Canada in the 1980s. With little space for gathering inside, the staff members at the time held their meeting in a small and cramped lunch room. Afterward, the CEO saw the station workers outside, joking around and hanging out in the trees like monkeys. In part inspired by the cable community, Teleglobe built a new, staff-friendly environment. The re-designed station grounded the communication hub in the heart of the cable family, yet left intact its Cold War foundations.

This northern suburb of Auckland, New Zealand, has been an outlet for northward communications for more than a century. In 1912, after a new Chief Post Office was opened in central Auckland, the Pacific Cable Board re-directed their cable from rural Doubtless Bay to Takapuna Beach. The workers from the station came with the cable, and the cable station was set up on in the Post Office, consolidating networks formerly distributed across the land. As the cable continued to function without major disruptions, networks in the following decades were routed through the suburban beach. When the Southern Cross internet cable was set up in 2000, it too landed on the Takapuna shore. In the cable industry, the prevailing logic is to go with the tried and true.
A link between Penang and Rangoon was manufactured by Telcon and laid by the Eastern Extension Australasia & China Telegraph Company in 1877.

Originally named Yangon in the 1700s, “end of strife” in Burmese, the city’s name was perverted under British colonial rule a century later. At the convergence of two major rivers, Rangoon is about 30 kilometers inland from the Gulf of Martaban. In 1877, the British laid a cable across the Andaman Sea, connecting Rangoon to nearby Penang. As it was built up into a colonial political center and commercial hub, the rivers served as excellent trade routes. An army engineer was enlisted to design a gridded, western-style city. When the cable arrived, Rangoon boasted sprawling parks, wealthy suburbs, lakes, hospitals, and a mix of colonial and traditional architecture. The telegraph office was established in a large, four story red brick building with ionic columns marking the entrance. Although the British rule disappeared in 1948, following great strife and a protracted struggle for independence, this building still stands today. Myanmar's first and, as of 2014, only fiber-optic link, lands about 75 miles south in coastal Pyapon. The country's inclusion in this system also depended on external support, as in the colonial era, it is only one small stop in a globe-spanning network.

http://rdfs.org/sioc/ns#content.value: Since the 1880s, Chikura has been known for precision exercises tied to the ocean. Every year, a knife ceremony is held at a local shrine dedicated to the gods of seasoning and culinary arts. Seven or eight men fillet and plate a whole carp using nothing but a twenty-inch blade and a pair of foot-long chopsticks, honoring the town’s legacy as a fishing community. In 1989, Chikura became a site of underwater cable innovation. The first fiber-optic line between the U.S. and Japan landed here, less than fifty miles from central Tokyo, followed by many other cables in the 1990s and 2000s. More recently, the town has become a surfing hub. Several professional competitions are held on Setohama Beach, where well-formed waves crash opposite the prominent cable station.

You make your way through sludge and silt to come ashore – quite a different experience from the clear seawater of the southern Japanese islands. A Spanish and then Dutch colony in the seventeenth century, Tanshui (also known as Dansheui) grew to become the largest port in Taiwan by the late 1800s. Coal and tea were exported in vast quantities from the natural harbor where the Tanshui (or Tamsui) River meets the Strait of Taiwan. In 1887, an underwater telegraph cable joined the bustling city to Fuzhou on the Chinese mainland, and a year later the Taipei Telegraph Academy opened nearby. But in the early twentieth century, the buildup of silt at the river mouth caused much of the shipping traffic to move east to Keelung. While its port status dwindled, Tanshui retained its position as an international cable hub. Several fiber-optic systems arrived in the early 2000s, linking the town to points throughout East Asia and the Pacific. Twin landing stations, owned by competing telecom carriers, are situated along a quiet beach west of the city, famous for vivid sunsets and a popular leisure destination for residents of Taipei.

http://rdfs.org/sioc/ns#content.value: Appropriately named Keoje, Korean for “great crossing,” this island is the landing site of several international submarine cable networks, though it is still smaller than the hub in nearby Pusan. As you come ashore through clear waters, the sound you hear is not heavy rainfall but the pebbles on Hakdong beach tumbling in the surf. Named after a crane (“hak” in Korean), this wing-shaped beach sits in a valley covered by flowering camellia plants, sheltered from the industrial shipyards and granite mines further north. Eschewing the discrete architecture of many contemporary cable facilities, the Korea Telecom landing station calls attention to itself with an ornate design. Decorative columns and topiaries line the station’s brick and glass entryway, which faces away from Hakdong’s beachfront promenade.

Entering service in 1997, the FLAG (Fiber-Optic Link Around the Globe) Europe-Asia cable system connects the United Kingdom with Japan via more than a dozen landing sites. The cable, now operated by an Indian telecom, was the subject of a 1996 Wired magazine article by cyberpunk author Neal Stephenson in which he traveled to “six countries and four continents trying to get a grip on this longest, fastest, mother of all wires.”

http://rdfs.org/sioc/ns#content.value: By the 1990s, capacity was filling up at Hong Kong’s major cable station, and the cable companies looked for a place to expand. Lantau Island, a few miles away from Hong Kong, seemed ideal. It was to be the site for major infrastructure developments during that period: a new Hong Kong airport, a trans-bay expressway, and the AsiaWorld theme park were placed in what was otherwise a sprawling, sparsely populated jungle. The station builders chose Tong Fuk, a small village on the island’s southern shore, for their landing. When they went to construct the station, however, the village leaders resisted, worried that the cable stations would disrupt the feng shui of the land and bring them bad fortune. The stations were ultimately placed there, but were careful not to infringe upon the nearby shrine.

The landing site at Ban Pak Bara in Satun province is Thailand’s only cable hub on the west coast and thus handles much of the country’s signal traffic to Europe and the Middle East. Some cables also continue from Satun overland to Songkhla, linking submarine networks in the Andaman Sea and Gulf of Thailand. Although a key international node, the station is overshadowed by its natural surroundings. From your landing place on the white sand beaches of this small fishing and agricultural community, you can see modest cinderblock communications buildings and towers across the road, surrounded by acres of mangrove trees. And looking back from where you came, your view is dominated by the lush and mountainous islands of Mu Ko Phetra National Park rising out of the water.

http://rdfs.org/sioc/ns#content.value: While many cable hubs remain concealed, the Melaka landing station is exceptionally visible. The large, sky-blue building towers over the houses in Pengkalan Balak, roughly fifteen miles north of central Melaka. A flag and bright signage mark the gated entryway. Following a series of Internet outages caused by high-profile earthquakes, Telekom Malaysia invited journalists to tour its station in order to expand awareness of the undersea network. http://rdfs.org/sioc/ns#content.value: In 1900, the Eastern Extension, Australasia and China Telegraph Company extended a link between Tschifu and Wei-hai-wei.

Tschifu is today called Yantai, meaning “smoky tower.” In a way, this harbor town was always a critical communications node: the name refers back to the Ming Dynasty, when locals would light smoky fires to warn the village of approaching Japanese pirates. On the north-eastern tip of the Shandong Peninsula, Tschifu was directly south of Dairen, due west of Seoul, and straight north from Shanghai. Its central location made it an ideal cable hub during the telegraph era. In the first decade of the twentieth century, ten cables were landed here, connecting to Tsingtau, Port Arthur, Taku, Dairen, Shanghai, and Wei-hai-wei. Even before the cables were landed, the city had long been an important traffic hub: it had been an international trading port for almost half a century and seventeen nations had established embassies there.

http://rdfs.org/sioc/ns#content.value: When the cable was landed in 1900, Wei-hai-wei was a British colony. On the northeastern edge of the Shandong Peninsula, the port town connected easily to Tschifu, just across the bay. Although they kept it an active port, the British never built up Wei-Hai-Wei as they did other nearby cities such as Shanghai. This was especially true after the Russo-Japanese War, when the Shandong Province was primarily controlled by Germany. Throughout the telegraph era, Wei-Hai-Wei remained a quiet harbor with small, traditional Chinese stone houses, dirt roads, canals, a cricket pitch, and parade grounds. The British military even built a sanatorium here, praising the location’s “temperate” and “healthy” climate.

http://rdfs.org/sioc/ns#content.value: Busan is a major gateway for East Asian cable traffic, with five submarine networks interconnecting at this station. It is also where some of the best seaweed in South Korea is grown, one cableman tells you. Unfortunately, the boom in South Korean seaweed production, which comprises over half of the country’s aquaculture, doesn’t benefit international signal traffic. Dense seaweed forests immediately off Busan’s shore twist around ropes bordering the cable’s path. Harvesting them, fishermen come close to the country’s international communications lines. When building a new system, cable companies aren’t allowed to dig into the seabed, since this might disturb the fragile seaweed’s growth. Instead they carefully place each cable in a “mattress” before lowering it down into the crop.

http://rdfs.org/sioc/ns#content.value: Carried by a secure, underwater cable from Guam, you land on Glass Beach, named for the abundant sea glass that can be found along the shore. Around you are the spherical radar stations and rocket launch facilities of the Ronald Regan Ballistic Missile Defense Test Site, which served as the command center for more than sixty U.S. nuclear tests in the Pacific after World War II. Kwajalein was a German colony in the late 1800s, then a Japanese trading post and naval stronghold in the early twentieth century until the U.S. took control in 1944. Despite being a vital node in U.S. defense networks, the island is physically small: just over one square mile and nine feet above sea level. Most residents travel by bicycle. And although the 2010 cable vastly increased communication speeds over existing satellite systems, it is also causing the base to shrink. The fiber-optic line allows more of the island’s military facilities to be operated remotely, thus reducing the need for on-site personnel.

Named after its owner, Hannon Armstrong, and operator Truestone, this system initially linked Guam to the Ronald Regan Ballistic Missile Defense Test Site in the Marshall Islands and was funded by the U.S. Army. In 2010, extensions were made to Majuro and the Federated States of Micronesia, greatly increasing speeds over existing satellite transmissions.

http://rdfs.org/sioc/ns#content.value: Built to receive the 2013 Southeast Asia Japan Cable, this station is controlled by the Brunei government in partnership with two telecom companies. Although it seems secluded, the town of Telisai is well connected by a coastal highway to neighboring districts. These include the country’s largest oil field, which produced its millionth barrel in 1991. Follow the road thirty miles east, and you will reach the main cable hub in Tungku. But first you’ll first pass the twin antennas of Brunei’s first satellite earth station, set up in 1979 and visible through a barbed wire fence. What appear to be snowdrifts on the hills around you are in fact silica sand deposits, formed long ago when sea levels were higher. Besides its white dunes, the region is perhaps best known for carnivorous pitcher plants, some of which are used in local cuisine.
